While an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce Ebola mortality, there are currently no drugs that have been proven to be effective in treating existing infections.
A cocktail of antibodies, ZMapp, initially proved to be promising, but formal studies showed that it, in terms of preventing deaths, brought fewer benefits than expected.
In the PALM study, ZMapp was used as a control, i.e. the scientists used it as a starting point and compared the three other treatments with it.
USA Gymnastics supports the letter of the United States Olympic Committee and accepts it as an absolute necessity that the Olympic family sets up a safe environment for all our athletes.
We agree with the statement of the USOC, that the interests of our athletes and clubs and their sport are better served by promoting sensible changes within our organization, rather than a decertification.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could shed light on how widespread abuse, as described so bravely by the survivors of Larry Nassar, could go undetected for so long, and welcomes all necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC have the same goal - to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for the athletes so that they can follow their dreams in a safe, positive and self-determined environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked as an advisor for John F. Kennedy and subsequently for the government around Lyndon B. Johnson.
During the elections in 1976, he advised Carter in foreign policy and then served from 1977 to 1981 in succession of Henry Kissinger as national security advisor (NSA).
As a national security adviser, he supported Carter in the diplomatic handling of world affairs such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the US and China in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution, which led to the Iran hostage crisis in 1979, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
