This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already widespread, but also provides details that fossils in general do not provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut-brown on the upper side and light- or carotinoid-colored on the underside.
The find also provides insights into the evolution of feathers in birds.
Because the dinosaur feathers do not have a well-developed shaft, which is called the rachis, but other features of feathers – barbs and barbules – the researchers concluded that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other features.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flying, but rather for temperature regulation or for display. The researchers suspected that the specimen, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, shows the feathers of an adult and not the down of a chick.
